Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels—For most of the last decade, central banks have made only limited progress in containing powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero while also undertaking multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have followed the Fed’s lead, implementing their own versions of what is known as “quantitative easing” (QE).
But inflation has failed to rise meaningfully anywhere.
Despite these countries all fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies – and economic performance – are diverging.
In the US and UK, growth is now strong enough to allow for the exit of expansionary policies and rate hikes, while the eurozone and Japan are ramping up QE to push policy long-term rates further into negative territory.
What accounts for this difference?
In short, it is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have run current account deficits, making them debtor nations, whereas the eurozone and Japan have maintained external surpluses, making them creditor nations.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations at the expense of creditor nations, so the negative interest rate stimulus introduced after the global economic crisis helped revive the US and the UK, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor nations worldwide – countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland – are experiencing negative interest rates, not just for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is far from good.
Despite low interest rates being ineffective, central banks in these economies continue to adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will divert to discussing how raising interest rates can stimulate the economy – which seems unassailable on the surface.
But in reality, it is full of holes.
Basic economics courses mention the curious phenomenon of the "backward-bending savings supply curve": under certain conditions, lowering interest rates leads to increased savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce savers' income, they will cut spending, especially if they are saving for retirement.
All of this does not negate the general rule – which forms the basis of modern monetary policy – that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other forms of spending.
Only the impact varies due to the different debt situations of economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so whatever creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should gain.
But in an economy with significant net foreign asset positions, creditors will naturally be more numerous than debtors.
For a country with substantial foreign debts, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effectiveness of lower bound monetary policy differs between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this was not important because foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
But now, the foreign asset positions of the major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly because of the leveraging that contributed to the global financial crisis of 2007–2008.
In fact, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
While current account imbalances have overall declined since the start of the financial crisis, they have not been reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, creating a divergence with deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, becoming major exceptions to the foreign asset position divergence.
Since June 2014, when world oil prices crashed, these countries’ wealth trends reversed.
Their export earnings plunged dramatically – many countries lost half of theirs – forcing them into deficits, relying on vast sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the commodity boom period.
Now, significant spending cuts are inevitable.
Industrialized economies face a completely different set of challenges.
Their problem – to some extent, a luxury problem – is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall they receive from lower import prices.
But in creditor nations, negative interest rates do not seem to be helping achieve this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence exists within the eurozone as well.
While the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it includes debtor nations.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have regular current account surpluses and are reducing their debt.
But traditional debtor countries' current account surpluses are too high, leading to an increasing asymmetry between debtor and creditor nations.
Most concerning is that since the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning Germany has accumulated surpluses during this period that exceed its historical totals.
Following current trends, Germany's creditor position could grow from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend toward central bank independence precisely because governors are less inclined to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to be running out of patience for low inflation, despite output gaps slowly being filled and full employment achieved in the US and Japan.
Central bank governors of debtor nations must stop using more monetary easing that could be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should let the recovery develop on its own, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effects from falling oil prices to disappear.
ECB governor Mario Draghi recently admitted that current monetary policy approaches may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same is not the solution.
